message.content:
A 'Lupinus arboreus' is a large shrub or a small tree that belongs to the family Fabaceae.
It is commonly known as tree lupine because of its treelike growth habit.
The height of the plant can reach up to 10 feet tall, with a spread of 6-8 feet.
It has large, silver-green leaves that are palmately composed of 5-8 leaflets.
The flowers are arranged in tall spikes and are typically bright yellow in color and fragrant.
Lupinus arboreus is native to California and Oregon and is often found growing in coastal scrub and chaparral habitats.
It is known to be a great attractor of pollinators such as bees, butterflies, and hummingbirds.
